vels was 1.46 (95% confidence interval (CI) 0.60-3.53) and 1.64 (95% CI 1.02-2.65) for CM and NMSC, respectively. The SRR for the highest versus lowest quintile of vitamin D intake was 0.86 (95% CI 0.63-1.13) for CM and 1.03 (95% CI 0.95-1.13) for NMSC. Data were suggestive of an inverse association between vitamin D blood levels and CM thickness at diagnosis. Further research is needed to investigate the effect of vitamin D on skin cancer risk in populations with different exposure to sunlight and dietary habits, and to evaluate whether vitamin D supplementation is effective in improving CM survival.";}s:13:"en_abstract_s";a:1:{i:0;s:1396:"Vitamin D is formed mainly in the skin upon exposure to sunlight and can as well be taken orally with food or through supplements. While sun exposure is a known risk factor for skin cancer development, vitamin D exerts anti-proliferative and pro-apoptotic effects on melanocytes and keratinocytes in vitro. To clarify the role of vitamin D in skin carcinogenesis, we performed a review of the literature and meta-analysis to evaluate the association of vitamin D serum levels and dietary intake with cutaneous melanoma (CM) and non-melanoma skin cancer (NMSC) risk and melanoma prognostic factors. Twenty papers were included for an overall 1420 CM and 2317 NMSC. The summary relative risks (SRRs) from random effects models for the association of highest versus lowest vitamin D serum levels was 1.46 (95% confidence interval (CI) 0.60-3.53) and 1.64 (95% CI 1.02-2.65) for CM and NMSC, respectively. The SRR for the highest versus lowest quintile of vitamin D intake was 0.86 (95% CI 0.63-1.13) for CM and 1.03 (95% CI 0.95-1.13) for NMSC. Data were suggestive of an inverse association between vitamin D blood levels and CM thickness at diagnosis. Further research is needed to investigate the effect of vitamin D on skin cancer risk in populations with different exposure to sunlight and dietary habits, and to evaluate whether vitamin D supplementation is effective in improving CM survival.";}s:28:"authIdHasPrimaryStructure_fs";a:10:{i:0;s:142:"1280663_FacetSep_S. Caini_JoinSep_453939_FacetSep_Unit of Molecular and Nutritional Epidemiology, Institute for Cancer Research and Prevention";i:1;s:93:"442956_FacetSep_M. Boniol_JoinSep_342907_FacetSep_International Prevention Research Institute";i:2;s:118:"157461_FacetSep_G. Tosti_JoinSep_453943_FacetSep_Division of Dermatoncological Surgery, European Institute of Oncology";i:3;s:118:"1280664_FacetSep_S. Magi_JoinSep_453944_FacetSep_Scientific Institute of Romagna for the Study and Treatment of Cancer";i:4;s:119:"1280665_FacetSep_M. Medri_JoinSep_453944_FacetSep_Scientific Institute of Romagna for the Study and Treatment of Cancer";i:5;s:125:"1280666_FacetSep_I. Stanganelli_JoinSep_453944_FacetSep_Scientific Institute of Romagna for the Study and Treatment of Cancer";i:6;s:142:"1279565_FacetSep_D. Palli_JoinSep_453939_FacetSep_Unit of Molecular and Nutritional Epidemiology, Institute for Cancer Research and Prevention";i:7;s:143:"1280667_FacetSep_M. Assedi_JoinSep_453939_FacetSep_Unit of Molecular and Nutritional Epidemiology, Institute for Cancer Research and Prevention";i:8;s:127:"1280668_FacetSep_V. D. Marmol_JoinSep_453945_FacetSep_Department of Dermatology. Hopital Erasme. Université Libre de Bruxelles";i:9;s:125:"496453_FacetSep_S. Gandini_JoinSep_453940_FacetSep_Division of Epidemiology and Biostatistics, European Institute of Oncology";}s:25:"structPrimaryHasAuthId_fs";a:10:{i:0;s:142:"453939_FacetSep_Unit of Molecular and Nutritional Epidemiology, Institute for Cancer Research and Prevention_JoinSep_1280663_FacetSep_S. Caini";i:1;s:93:"342907_FacetSep_International Prevention Research Institute_JoinSep_442956_FacetSep_M. Boniol";i:2;s:118:"453943_FacetSep_Division of Dermatoncological Surgery, European Institute of Oncology_JoinSep_157461_FacetSep_G. Tosti";i:3;s:118:"453944_FacetSep_Scientific Institute of Romagna for the Study and Treatment of Cancer_Jo