nt. Two of these models, called R224 and R22, are new and the others are Pacanowski and Philander's model (R213 model) and Gent's model (R23 model). The numerical implementation is based on a non-conservative numerical scheme. The following (three criteria) are used to compare the models: the surface current intensity, the thermocline's form and the mixed layer depth. We start by a first series of numerical tests where the initial density and the initial velocity profiles are linear. This case aims valid our finite difference code and then to spotlight the four models behavior in this particular case. Next, we initialize the code with realistic velocity and density profiles thanks the TOGA-TAO array (McPhaden, 1995). In case of unstatic instability zone on the initial density profile, only the R224 model gives realistic results. Furthermore, we study the equilibrium solution. It is a linear solution which is in agreement with Bennis and al.";}s:13:"en_abstract_s";a:1:{i:0;s:1260:"In this study, we compare four turbulence models usually used to parameterize the oceanic boundary layer. These four models depend on the bulk Richardson number, which is coherent with the studied region, the West Pacific Warm Pool, because of the large mean shear associated with the equatorial undercurrent. Two of these models, called R224 and R22, are new and the others are Pacanowski and Philander's model (R213 model) and Gent's model (R23 model). The numerical implementation is based on a non-conservative numerical scheme. The following (three criteria) are used to compare the models: the surface current intensity, the thermocline's form and the mixed layer depth. We start by a first series of numerical tests where the initial density and the initial velocity profiles are linear. This case aims valid our finite difference code and then to spotlight the four models behavior in this particular case. Next, we initialize the code with realistic velocity and density profiles thanks the TOGA-TAO array (McPhaden, 1995). In case of unstatic instability zone on the initial density profile, only the R224 model gives realistic results. Furthermore, we study the equilibrium solution. It is a linear solution which is in agreement with Bennis and al.";}s:28:"authIdHasPrimaryStructure_fs";a:5:{i:0;s:100:"153431_FacetSep_Anne-Claire Bennis_JoinSep_75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes";i:1;s:122:"710323_FacetSep_Macarena Gómez Marmol_JoinSep_27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenciales y Analisis Numerico";i:2;s:98:"46674_FacetSep_Roger Lewandowski_JoinSep_75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes";i:3;s:121:"1036303_FacetSep_Tomas Chacon-Rebollo_JoinSep_27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenciales y Analisis Numerico";i:4;s:101:"159247_FacetSep_Françoise Brossier_JoinSep_75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes";}s:25:"structPrimaryHasAuthId_fs";a:5:{i:0;s:100:"75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes_JoinSep_153431_FacetSep_Anne-Claire Bennis";i:1;s:122:"27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenciales y Analisis Numerico_JoinSep_710323_FacetSep_Macarena Gómez Marmol";i:2;s:98:"75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes_JoinSep_46674_FacetSep_Roger Lewandowski";i:3;s:121:"27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenciales y Analisis Numerico_JoinSep_1036303_FacetSep_Tomas Chacon-Rebollo";i:4;s:101:"75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes_JoinSep_159247_FacetSep_Françoise Brossier";}s:28:"structPrimaryHasAuthIdHal_fs";a:5:{i:0;s:112:"75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes_JoinSep_anne-claire-bennis_FacetSep_Bennis Anne-Claire";i:1;s:116:"27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenciales y Analisis Numerico_JoinSep__FacetSep_Gómez Marmol Macarena";i:2;s:93:"75_FacetSep_Institut de Recherche Mathématique de Rennes_JoinSep__FacetSep_Lewandowski Roger";i:3;s:114:"27941_FacetSep_Departamento de Ecuaciones Diferenci